  "narrative": {
    "one_liner": "Three days on the grid: solar floods midday, demand surges at dusk. Tame the duck curve or pay the price.",
    "teaching_moment": "No forecast is available. Use the current telemetry \u2014 demand, solar, price, and SOC \u2014 to decide when to charge, discharge, and curtail. The steep evening ramp is the defining challenge: power plants cannot ramp up fast, and neither should your grid import. Battery smoothing and strategic curtailment are the keys to low cost.",
    "context": "You're operating a single-node distribution feeder for three simulated days. Midday solar regularly exceeds local demand (the 'belly' of the duck), and the steep evening ramp from sunset to peak demand (the 'neck') is the costliest moment of every day. Your job: charge the battery during the solar belly, discharge into the evening peak, and curtail solar only when export would be more costly than wasting it. Score is the raw cost sum over the whole run \u2014 lower wins.",
    "explainer_url": ""
  },
